    68	
    69	### Scaling — latency is ~O(N) (no ANN index on vec0)
    70	
    71	The vec0 bit-KNN is a per-query **linear** scan over all N rows (no HNSW/IVF
    72	index; see `dev/notes/ac013-ac019-canonical-scale-policy.md` "long-term
    73	follow-up"). The measured synthetic points confirm near-linear growth:
    74	
    75	| dim | N=10K p50 | N=100K p50 | ratio (10×N) | implied 1M p50 (linear) |
    76	|---|---|---|---|---|
    77	| 384 (prod) | 15 ms | 147 ms | 9.8× | ~1,470 ms |
    78	| 768 | 22 ms | 190 ms | 8.6× | ~1,900 ms |
    79	
    80	So at the shipped 384-d, p50 is ~**O(N)** with coefficient ≈ **1.5 ms per
    81	1,000 docs** plus a small fixed per-query overhead (the FTS MATCH + soft-
    82	fallback probe + parse run on every `search()` regardless of N). The 10k
    83	binding-tier number is **15 ms (synthetic 384-d) / 36 ms (real bge, N=7667
    84	≈ 10k)**; linear scaling sets the 100k tier near 147 ms and the 1M tier near
    85	1.5 s — i.e. the 80 ms p50 budget is **not** met above ~50k without an ANN
    86	index. This is the data behind the tiered ADR decision (10k binding for
    87	0.x/1.x; 100k/1M tracked targets for post-1.0, pre-2.1 ANN work).
    88	
    89	### Seed-cost finding (why 1M did not complete locally)
    90	
    91	Seeding is **super-linear** on the default per-row projection path:
    92	N=100K drained in ~182 s (~550 docs/s), but N=1M did **not** drain in 3 h
    93	(`wait_for_idle` timeout → `Err(Scheduler)`; **not** a wedge — see
    94	`Engine::drain` at `lib.rs:1995`). vec0 b-tree insertion + sign-bit quantize
    95	+ WAL growth cost rises with table size. 0.7.0 obtained its 1M number only via
    96	the W4.1 perf-knob seed path (pcache2 + `page_size=8192`), which the plain
    97	`cargo test` path here does not enable. The 1M tier is therefore recorded from
    98	the 0.7.0 W4.1 historical anchor + the O(N) extrapolation above, not a fresh
    99	local run.
